## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also removed** — no abort/reset pattern exists
3. The idiomatic replacement is `CancellationToken` + `Task` with cooperative cancellation

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates to match original behavior
            throw ex.InnerExceptions[0];
        }
    }

    // Overload for fire-and-forget work that can't accept a token
    // ⚠️  Cannot forcibly kill — the delegate runs to completion
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        var task = Task.Run(work);

        if (task.Wait(timeout))
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }

        // Task is still running — we can't stop it
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout. " +
            "WARNING: the background work is still running.");
    }
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No forced termination** | .NET 8 has no `Thread.Abort`. The non-token overload *abandons* the work — it keeps running. Leaked threads/resources are possible. |
| **Cooperative cancellation required** | Callers must check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or pass the token to I/O APIs. Without checks, timeout only affects the *caller*, not the work. |
| **`Task.Run` uses the ThreadPool** | Original code created a dedicated thread. For very long-running blocking work, consider `Task.Factory.StartNew(..., TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning)`. |
| **Exception wrapping changed** | `Task.Run` wraps in `AggregateException`; the migrated code unwraps single exceptions to preserve original behavior. |

### Example Caller Migration

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => SlowQuery(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// After (.NET 8) — pass token into the work
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();  // check periodically
    return SlowQuery(token);              // pass to downstream APIs
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**Bottom line:** There is no drop-in replacement for `Thread.Abort`. The migration *requires* changing work delegates to accept and honor a `CancellationToken`. The non-token overload is provided only as a transitional shim — it cannot actually stop runaway work.
